					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-2275654#post-3895877</guid>
				<title>+1 for my feels</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-2275654/scp-3900#post-3895877</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Thu, 02 Aug 2018 18:31:49 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Yukichigai</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>2764087</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>As someone who has worked both on the hardware and software side of computers and computer support, this had me rolling on the floor from both laughter and sympathetic pain. Strip out the supernatural element and it feels eerily like any number of sessions of troubleshooting I've done:</p> <ol> <li>Weird error is reported. Even better, it only crops up at a certain time. Troubleshooting commences.</li> <li>For some reason it seems to track to a completely unrelated aspect of the system, which makes no sense but whatever. Do some tests to confirm.</li> <li>Just when you think you've at least figured out the scope of the thing, you figure out the error is affecting something else in a weirdly different but related way. Even better, the error output doesn't make any sense, even though it's obviously related.</li> <li>Start testing the new, secondary error. Joy of joys you find out it affects something else in an even weirder way.</li> <li>Test the tertiary error. At this point you get an interaction that is mostly hilarious if it wasn't for the part where it might destroy the system in the wrong circumstance. It makes sense in that it's related, but doesn't make sense in that HOW IS THAT EVEN POSSIBLE?!</li> <li>Throw up your hands, tell whoever reported the error to just get a new router/computer/whatever.</li> </ol> <p>+1</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
